data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern — `Thread.Abort()` forcibly kills a thread that exceeds a deadline, with `ThreadAbortException`/`ResetAbort` as the safety net. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `ResetAbort` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`).

The replacement is **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work func MUST check the token for cancellation to actually stop.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Thread pool is more efficient; `Task` integrates with cancellation |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Abort throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed — cancellation doesn't forcibly inject exceptions |
| `Func<T> work` | `Func<CancellationToken, T> work` | Work **must** receive the token to cooperate |

### Critical Pitfall: Cancellation Is Not Automatic

With `Thread.Abort`, the runtime *forcibly injected* an exception — the work didn't need to cooperate. With `CancellationToken`, **the work must voluntarily check for cancellation**. If it doesn't, it runs forever.

Callers must update their work functions:

```csharp
// BEFORE — work ignores cancellation (this "worked" with Thread.Abort)
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() =>
{
    foreach (var item in hugelist)
        Process(item);    // Thread.Abort would kill this mid-loop
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// AFTER — work cooperates with the token
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### If You Cannot Modify the Work (Uncooperative Code)

If `work` is opaque code you can't change (e.g., third-party library), cooperative cancellation won't help. You have two options:

**Option A — Abandon the task** (thread-pool thread keeps running but you stop waiting):

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();

    // Task is still running — we just stop waiting.
    // ⚠️ The work is NOT cancelled; it continues on a thread-pool thread.
    throw new TimeoutException(
        $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
}
```

**Option B — Move work to a child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. This is the only true equivalent of `Thread.Abort` for uncooperative code.

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Solution |
|---|---|
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Always wrap in `using` — leaking it leaks timers |
| Adding token parameter but never checking it in loops | Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints |
| Expecting `Thread.Sleep` to respond to the token | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it | Let it propagate; only catch at the top-level orchestration point |
| Not passing token through the full call chain | Every method in the chain must forward the `CancellationToken` |
